<text>Introduction to Crystals
p. 2 of 8
Crystals are common forms of solids.  They are characterized by their order, compared with the disorder of liquids and the independence of atoms in gases. They are made of repeating units that can be as simple as a single kind of atom or as complex as a protein molecule.

   

Imagine we have created a slice through a crystal that is only one atom deep.  Run the model by clicking the PLAY arrow    of the player. Notice how the particles move and the ways in which they are constrained. Then, focus on one atom that is not on the edge, and look the atoms around it. Repeat for other atoms. What do you notice? 
 

   

</text>
